bug.short_desc: [test] Make compiler test run with APT enabled

long_desc.thetext:
See bug 436486 for context. At times having APT enabled affects the compiler behavior as seen in the given bug.
This bug is to investigate the options to run the compiler tests with APT enabled ,possibly with dummy annotations processors.

Created attachment 249507 Change to test framework
This patch as is causes quite a few test failures and some of them go away with the proposed fix to bug 436486 included.
I haven't looked at all failures, but looks like they needs to be addressed.

Created attachment 249509 Failure list
As of now, there are about 29 failing tests at 1.8 level, probably falling into less than a dozen buckets.

BTW, it's worth mentioning that this change results in tests taking about 10% more time than usual (no scientific method used, though). Perhaps we should run the APT enabled compiler tests only at 1.8 level.

(In reply to Jayaprakash Arthanareeswaran from comment #3) > BTW, it's worth mentioning that this change results in tests taking about > 10% more time than usual (no scientific method used, though). Perhaps we > should run the APT enabled compiler tests only at 1.8 level.
I'm happy to see that this mode of testing is possible! OTOH, I'm not keen on running these during *every* build. In particular we wouldn't want to run all tests always with APT and thus miss any potential problems that might occur only in absence of APT :p
I wonder if we might want to define a special testing profile that is used only shortly before a milestone. That way we could have the best of both worlds: timely test results during regular builds and added safety before a milestone.
Another candidate for this extra-safety-net: run compiler tests with comparison to javac output. What other tests are not included in our automated suite? I know of NullReferenceImplTests, are there more?
At the other end of the spectrum I could also imagine reducing regular test runs to exercising only - say - 1.7 and 1.8 compliance levels, leaving the older levels to the less frequent test runs.

(In reply to Stephan Herrmann from comment #5) > Another candidate for this extra-safety-net: run compiler tests with > comparison to javac output. What other tests are not included in our > automated suite? I know of NullReferenceImplTests, are there more?
Run all tests with null annotation analysis enabled (perhaps with some magic to ignore additional errors/warnings). If we agree on the overall strategy I'll be happy to provide this one.

This patch here:
https://git.eclipse.org/r/#/c/38528/
provides a way individual tests or entire compiler suite can be run with APT enabled. To run all tests with APT hooked in, set the JVM parameter "enableAPT", i.e., pass -DenableAPT . Or individual tests can use this additional testing mechanism by simply setting this field at the beginnin of the test:
this.enableAPT = true;
And of course, reset it back to what it was in the beginning.
Verified for 4.5 M5 by inspection using I20150127-0900 build
